<TITLE> Europe shares rise, relief over banks buoys stocks </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Oct 2 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares rose early on Tuesday, boosted by banks as investors took the view that the worst of the credit crunch may be over, while UK retailer Tesco gained after reporting first-half earnings. By 0713 GMT the FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares was up 0.7 percent at 1,574.46 points. Not all analysts were confident the fallout of the credit crunch has peaked, however, as the index is still about 4 percent off the six-and-half year highs seen in mid-July. "I think it's bit too quick to say it's done now," said Heinz-Gerd Sonnenschein, a strategist at Germany's Postbank. "We've seen huge (losses) at UBS, at Citigroup ... we can say next quarter will be better and the whole year will be okay, but I think these will not be the last companies we will see with problems coming out around subprime," he said. Global equities earlier hit a record high, while the Dow Jones secured a record close on Monday and Tokyo stocks touched their highest in eight weeks. London's FTSE 100 index was up 0.9 percent, while Frankfurt's DAX gained 0.4 percent and Paris' CAC 40 rose 0.6 percent. Shares in Tesco, the world's third-largest retailer, rose 3 percent making it one of the top weighted gainers on the FTSEurofirst after reporting a slowdown in growth in its core British market in the half year, but beating expectations with like-for-like sal
